00:01:35.475 --> 00:01:38.694
so that you can kinda see the
formula and then how we apply it.

00:01:38.694 --> 00:01:43.694
So, it's the square root of one
plus f-prime of x squared d x.

00:01:46.469 --> 00:01:50.920
And in this case, it's going
to be the definite integral

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:55.920
from zero to 32/9 of the
square root of one plus...

00:02:00.511 --> 00:02:01.557
Now, what's the derivative?

00:02:01.557 --> 00:02:06.557
If f of x is x to the 3/2,
then f-prime of x is going

00:02:09.052 --> 00:02:13.135
to be 3/2 x to the 1/2.

00:02:13.135 --> 00:02:15.128
And we picked this particular function

00:02:15.128 --> 00:02:18.426
because it simplifies
quite well when we put it

00:02:18.426 --> 00:02:20.690
under the radical, and
it's fairly straightforward

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:22.513
to find the anti-derivative.

00:02:22.513 --> 00:02:24.946
So we've done a lot of
engineering of this problem

00:02:24.946 --> 00:02:26.394
to make the numbers work out well,

00:02:26.394 --> 00:02:27.797
but let's just go through it.

00:02:27.797 --> 00:02:32.517
So this is f-prime of x;
f-prime of x squared is going

00:02:32.517 --> 00:02:33.984
to be this quantity squared.

00:02:33.984 --> 00:02:38.600
It's going to be 9/4 x
to the 1/2 squared is x.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:43.600
So, one plus 9/4 x d x.

00:02:43.716 --> 00:02:45.850
And so, now, we just
have a definite integral

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:48.323
that we know how to
solve this type of thing.

00:02:48.323 --> 00:02:50.589
And you might be able to
even do this in your head,

00:02:50.589 --> 00:02:52.241
essentially, do the u-substitution:

00:02:52.241 --> 00:02:54.583
say I have one plus 9/4 x.

00:02:54.583 --> 00:02:56.297
